{"title_page": "Soyuz MS-16", "text_new": "{{short description|Spaceflight mission}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox spaceflight\n| name           = Soyuz MS-16\n| image          = \n| image_caption  = \n| insignia       = [[File:Soyuz-MS-16-Mission-Patch.png|250px]]\n\n| mission_type       = Crewed mission to ISS\n| operator           = [[Roscosmos]]\n| COSPAR_ID          = 2020-023A\n| SATCAT             = 45465\n| mission_duration   = {{time interval|2020-04-09 08:05:06||show=dhm|abbr=on}} ''(in progress)''\n| distance_travelled = \n| orbits_completed   = \n\n| spacecraft      = Soyuz-MS\n| spacecraft_type = [[Soyuz-MS]] 11F747\n| manufacturer    = [[RKK Energia]]\n| launch_mass     = 7280 kg\n| landing_mass    = \n\n| launch_date       = 9 April 2020, 08:05:06 UTC <ref name=interfax-20190627>{{cite news|url=https://www.militarynews.ru/story.asp?rid=1&nid=511433&lang=RU|title=\u0423\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0436\u0434\u0435\u043d \u044d\u043a\u0438\u043f\u0430\u0436 \u043a\u043e\u0441\u043c\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043a\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0431\u043b\u044f \"\u0421\u043e\u044e\u0437 \u041c\u0421-16\"|language=ru|trans-title=The crew of MS-16 Soyuz spacecraft has been approved|agency=[[Interfax]]|date=27 June 2019|access-date=28 August 2019}}</ref>\n| launch_rocket     = [[Soyuz-2.1a]]\n| launch_contractor = [[Progress Rocket Space Centre]]\n| launch_site       = [[Baikonur Cosmodrome|Baikonur]], [[Baikonur Cosmodrome Site 31|Site 31/6]]\n| landing_date      = \n| landing_site      = \n\n| crew_size          = 3\n| crew_members       = [[Anatoli Ivanishin]]<br/>[[Ivan Vagner]]<br/>[[Christopher Cassidy]]\n| crew_callsign      = Irkut\n| crew_photo         = ISS Expedition 63 prime crew (jsc2020e014994).jpg\n| crew_photo_caption = Chris Cassidy, Anatoly Ivanishin and Ivan Vagner\n\n| orbit_reference   = [[Geocentric orbit|Geocentric]]\n| orbit_regime      = [[Low Earth orbit|Low Earth]]\n| orbit_altitude    = 419 - 440 km <ref name=SF/>\n| orbit_periapsis   = \n| orbit_apoapsis    = \n| orbit_inclination = 51.64\u00b0 <ref name=SF/>\n| orbit_period      = \n| apsis             = gee\n\n| docking = {{Infobox spaceflight/Dock\n   | docking_target = [[International Space Station|ISS]]\n   | docking_type   = dock\n   | docking_port   = [[Poisk (ISS module)|Poisk]] zenith\n   | docking_date   = 9 April 2020, 14:13:18 UTC <ref name=SF/>\n   | undocking_date = \n   | time_docked    = {{time interval|2020-04-09 14:13:18||show=dhm|abbr=on}}\n}}\n| previous_mission = [[Soyuz MS-15]]\n| next_mission     = [[Soyuz MS-17]]\n| programme        = [[Soyuz programme]]<br/><small>(Crewed missions)</small>\n}}\n\n'''Soyuz MS-16''' was a [[Soyuz (spacecraft)|Soyuz]] spaceflight launched on 9 April 2020,<ref name=interfax-20190627/> transporting three members of the [[Expedition 62]] crew to the [[International Space Station]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spacefacts.de/iss/english/exp_62.htm|title=ISS: Expedition 62|work=spacefacts.de|date=20 February 2020|accessdate=20 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThis flight was the first crewed launch using the [[Soyuz 2.1a]] rocket, and the first crewed Russian mission not to launch from [[Gagarin's Start]] \u2014 the pad at [[Baikonur Cosmodrome]] that was before its planned modernisation for Soyuz-2 rockets after [[Soyuz MS-15]] \u2014 since [[Soyuz MS-02]] in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spacefacts.de/mission/english/soyuz-ms-02.htm|title=Soyuz MS-02 |work=spacefacts.de|date=20 April 2018|accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Crew==\n{{Spaceflight crew\n|terminology = Crew member\n\n|position1      = Commander\n|crew1_up       = {{flagicon|RUS}} [[Anatoli Ivanishin]]\n|agency1_up     = [[Russian Federal Space Agency|RSA]]\n|flights1_up    = Third\n|expedition1_up = Expedition 62\n\n|position2      = Flight Engineer 1\n|crew2_up       = {{flagicon|RUS}} [[Ivan Vagner]]\n|agency2_up     = [[Russian Federal Space Agency|RSA]]\n|flights2_up    = First\n|expedition2_up = Expedition 62\n\n|position3      = Flight Engineer 2\n|crew3_up       = {{Flagicon|USA}} [[Christopher Cassidy]]\n|agency3_up     = [[NASA]]\n|flights3_up    = Third\n|expedition3_up = Expedition 62\n}}\n\n===Backup crew=== \n{{Spaceflight crew\n|terminology = Crew member<ref name=SF>{{cite web|url=http://www.spacefacts.de/mission/english/soyuz-ms-16.htm|title=Soyuz MS-16|work=spacefacts.de|date=20 February 2020|accessdate=20 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n|position1      = Commander\n|crew1_up       = {{flagicon|RUS}} [[Sergey Ryzhikov (cosmonaut)|Sergey Ryzhikov]]\n|agency1_up     = [[Russian Federal Space Agency|RSA]]\n|flights1_up    = \n|expedition1_up = \n\n|position2      = Flight Engineer 1\n|crew2_up       = {{flagicon|RUS}} [[Andrei Babkin]]\n|agency2_up     = [[Russian Federal Space Agency|RSA]]\n|flights2_up    = \n|expedition2_up = \n\n|position3      = Flight Engineer 2\n|crew3_up       = {{Flagicon|USA}} [[Stephen Bowen (astronaut)|Stephen Bowen]] \n|agency3_up     = [[NASA]]\n|flights3_up    = \n|expedition3_up = \n}}\n\n===Crew notes===\nThis flight would have marked the first spaceflight for rookie cosmonaut [[Nikolai Tikhonov (cosmonaut)|Nikolai Tikhonov]], who has been removed from several ISS flights due to delays to the Russian [[Nauka (ISS module)|Nauka]] Laboratory module starting with [[Soyuz MS-04]]. Tikhonov and Babkin were replaced by their backups, Ivanishin and Vagner, for medical reasons.<ref>{{cite web|last=Clark|first=Stephen |url=https://spaceflightnow.com/2020/02/19/russian-space-agency-replaces-cosmonauts-on-next-space-station-crew/|title=Russian space agency replaces cosmonauts on next space station crew|work=Spaceflight Now |date=19 February 2020|accessdate=20 February 2020}}</ref> The cosmonaut Nikolai Tikhonov, the original Soyuz commander, suffered an eye injury and Russian officials opted to swap both Russian crew members with the back-up crew.<ref name=Qua/>\n\nDue to the [[coronavirus pandemic]], the crew families and the media representatives couldn't watch the launch in Baikonur, and the usual pre-launch traditions dating since Yuri Gagarin have been cancelled.<ref name=Qua>{{Cite web|url=https://spaceflightnow.com/2020/03/20/astronauts-family-wont-attend-launch-next-month-due-to-coronavirus-threat/|title=Astronaut's family won't attend launch next month due to coronavirus threat|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 22, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322220527/https://spaceflightnow.com/2020/03/20/astronauts-family-wont-attend-launch-next-month-due-to-coronavirus-threat/|archivedate=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Portal|Spaceflight}}\n{{Soyuz}}\n{{Manned ISS flight}}\n{{Orbital launches in 2020}}\n{{People currently in space}}\n\n[[Category:Crewed Soyuz missions]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft launched in 2020]]\n[[Category:2020 in Russia]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft launched by Soyuz-2 rockets\u200e]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Spaceflight mission}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox spaceflight\n| name           = Soyuz MS-16\n| image          = \n| image_caption  = \n| insignia       = [[File:Soyuz-MS-16-Mission-Patch.png|250px]]\n\n| mission_type       = Crewed mission to ISS\n| operator           = [[Roscosmos]]\n| COSPAR_ID          = 2020-023A\n| SATCAT             = 45465\n| mission_duration   = {{time interval|2020-04-09 08:05:06||show=dhm|abbr=on}} ''(in progress)''\n| distance_travelled = \n| orbits_completed   = \n\n| spacecraft      = Soyuz-MS\n| spacecraft_type = [[Soyuz-MS]] 11F747\n| manufacturer    = [[RKK Energia]]\n| launch_mass     = 7280 kg\n| landing_mass    = \n\n| launch_date       = 9 April 2020, 08:05:06 UTC <ref name=interfax-20190627>{{cite news|url=https://www.militarynews.ru/story.asp?rid=1&nid=511433&lang=RU|title=\u0423\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0436\u0434\u0435\u043d \u044d\u043a\u0438\u043f\u0430\u0436 \u043a\u043e\u0441\u043c\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043a\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0431\u043b\u044f \"\u0421\u043e\u044e\u0437 \u041c\u0421-16\"|language=ru|trans-title=The crew of MS-16 Soyuz spacecraft has been approved|agency=[[Interfax]]|date=27 June 2019|access-date=28 August 2019}}</ref>\n| launch_rocket     = [[Soyuz-2.1a]]\n| launch_contractor = [[Progress Rocket Space Centre]]\n| launch_site       = [[Baikonur Cosmodrome|Baikonur]], [[Baikonur Cosmodrome Site 31|Site 31/6]]\n| landing_date      = \n| landing_site      = \n\n| crew_size          = 3\n| crew_members       = [[Anatoli Ivanishin]]<br/>[[Ivan Vagner]]<br/>[[Christopher Cassidy]]\n| crew_callsign      = Irkut\n| crew_photo         = ISS Expedition 63 prime crew (jsc2020e014994).jpg\n| crew_photo_caption = Chris Cassidy, Anatoly Ivanishin and Ivan Vagner\n\n| orbit_reference   = [[Geocentric orbit|Geocentric]]\n| orbit_regime      = [[Low Earth orbit|Low Earth]]\n| orbit_altitude    = 419 - 440 km<ref name=SF />\n| orbit_periapsis   = \n| orbit_apoapsis    = \n| orbit_inclination = 51.64\u00b0<ref name=SF />\n| orbit_period      = \n| apsis             = gee\n\n| docking = {{Infobox spaceflight/Dock\n   | docking_target = [[International Space Station|ISS]]\n   | docking_type   = dock\n   | docking_port   = [[Poisk (ISS module)|Poisk]] zenith\n   | docking_date   = 9 April 2020, 14:13:18 UTC <ref name=SF />\n   | undocking_date = \n   | time_docked    = {{time interval|2020-04-09 14:13:18||show=dhm|abbr=on}}\n}}\n| previous_mission = [[Soyuz MS-15]]\n| next_mission     = [[Soyuz MS-17]]\n| programme        = [[Soyuz programme]]<br/><small>(Crewed missions)</small>\n}}\n\n'''Soyuz MS-16''' was a [[Soyuz (spacecraft)|Soyuz]] spaceflight launched on 9 April 2020,<ref name=interfax-20190627/> transporting three members of the [[Expedition 62]] crew to the [[International Space Station]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spacefacts.de/iss/english/exp_62.htm|title=ISS: Expedition 62|work=spacefacts.de|date=20 February 2020|accessdate=20 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThis flight was the first crewed launch using the [[Soyuz 2.1a]] rocket, and the first crewed Russian mission not to launch from [[Gagarin's Start]] \u2014 the pad at [[Baikonur Cosmodrome]] that was before its planned modernisation for Soyuz-2 rockets after [[Soyuz MS-15]] \u2014 since [[Soyuz MS-02]] in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spacefacts.de/mission/english/soyuz-ms-02.htm|title=Soyuz MS-02 |work=spacefacts.de|date=20 April 2018 |accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Crew==\n{{Spaceflight crew\n|terminology = Crew member\n\n|position1      = Commander\n|crew1_up       = {{flagicon|RUS}} [[Anatoli Ivanishin]]\n|agency1_up     = [[Russian Federal Space Agency|RSA]]\n|flights1_up    = Third\n|expedition1_up = Expedition 62\n\n|position2      = Flight Engineer 1\n|crew2_up       = {{flagicon|RUS}} [[Ivan Vagner]]\n|agency2_up     = [[Russian Federal Space Agency|RSA]]\n|flights2_up    = First\n|expedition2_up = Expedition 62\n\n|position3      = Flight Engineer 2\n|crew3_up       = {{Flagicon|USA}} [[Christopher Cassidy]]\n|agency3_up     = [[NASA]]\n|flights3_up    = Third\n|expedition3_up = Expedition 62\n}}\n\n===Backup crew=== \n{{Spaceflight crew\n|terminology = Crew member<ref name=SF>{{cite web|url=http://www.spacefacts.de/mission/english/soyuz-ms-16.htm|title=Soyuz MS-16|work=spacefacts.de|date=20 February 2020|accessdate=20 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n|position1      = Commander\n|crew1_up       = {{flagicon|RUS}} [[Sergey Ryzhikov (cosmonaut)|Sergey Ryzhikov]]\n|agency1_up     = [[Russian Federal Space Agency|RSA]]\n|flights1_up    = \n|expedition1_up = \n\n|position2      = Flight Engineer 1\n|crew2_up       = {{flagicon|RUS}} [[Andrei Babkin]]\n|agency2_up     = [[Russian Federal Space Agency|RSA]]\n|flights2_up    = \n|expedition2_up = \n\n|position3      = Flight Engineer 2\n|crew3_up       = {{Flagicon|USA}} [[Stephen Bowen (astronaut)|Stephen Bowen]] \n|agency3_up     = [[NASA]]\n|flights3_up    = \n|expedition3_up = \n}}\n\n===Crew notes===\nThis flight would have marked the first spaceflight for rookie cosmonaut [[Nikolai Tikhonov (cosmonaut)|Nikolai Tikhonov]], who has been removed from several ISS flights due to delays to the Russian [[Nauka (ISS module)|Nauka]] Laboratory module starting with [[Soyuz MS-04]]. Tikhonov and Babkin were replaced by their backups, Ivanishin and Vagner, for medical reasons.<ref>{{cite web|last=Clark|first=Stephen |url=https://spaceflightnow.com/2020/02/19/russian-space-agency-replaces-cosmonauts-on-next-space-station-crew/|title=Russian space agency replaces cosmonauts on next space station crew|work=Spaceflight Now |date=19 February 2020|accessdate=20 February 2020}}</ref> The cosmonaut Nikolai Tikhonov, the original Soyuz commander, suffered an eye injury and Russian officials opted to swap both Russian crew members with the back-up crew.<ref name=Qua/>\n\nDue to the [[coronavirus pandemic]], the crew families and the media representatives couldn't watch the launch in Baikonur, and the usual pre-launch traditions dating since Yuri Gagarin have been cancelled.<ref name=Qua>{{Cite web|url=https://spaceflightnow.com/2020/03/20/astronauts-family-wont-attend-launch-next-month-due-to-coronavirus-threat/|title=Astronaut's family won't attend launch next month due to coronavirus threat|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 22, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322220527/https://spaceflightnow.com/2020/03/20/astronauts-family-wont-attend-launch-next-month-due-to-coronavirus-threat/|archivedate=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Portal|Spaceflight}}\n{{Soyuz}}\n{{Manned ISS flight}}\n{{Orbital launches in 2020}}\n{{People currently in space}}\n\n[[Category:Crewed Soyuz missions]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft launched in 2020]]\n[[Category:2020 in Russia]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft launched by Soyuz-2 rockets\u200e]]\n", "name_user": "CRS-20", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soyuz_MS-16"}
{"title_page": "Casey Kaplan", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2015}}\n'''Casey Kaplan''' is a contemporary [[art gallery]] in [[New York City]], in the United States.\n\n==History==\nThe gallery was founded in 1995 in a {{convert|500|sqft|m2|abbr=on}}, one-room space located on the upper floor of a cast iron loft building on Broadway, before moving to Greene Street in 1997. The gallery relocated in 2000 to a store-front gallery space in [[Chelsea, Manhattan|Chelsea]] / [[Meatpacking District, Manhattan|Meatpacking District]] on 14th Street. During this time, Casey Kaplan hosted the first ever New York solo exhibitions of many now canonized contemporary artists, such as Jason Dodge, [[Trisha Donnelly]], [[Carsten H\u00f6ller]], [[Jonathan Monk]] and [[Simon Starling]], in addition to staging solo shows with [[Liam Gillick]] and curatorial collaborations with [[Daniel Birnbaum]] and artist [[Douglas Gordon]].\n\nThe gallery expanded once more in 2005 to a larger store-front on 21st street, before relocating in 2015 to our current {{convert|10000|sqft|m2|abbr=on}}, two-story space in the Flower District. Solo exhibitions in the new space have been staged by [[Kevin Beasley]], [[Jordan Casteel]], [[Sarah Crowner]], N. Dash, [[Haris Epaminonda]], [[Geoffrey Farmer]], Mateo L\u00f3pez, and [[Matthew Ronay]], and the distinguished Turin-based abstract painter [[Giorgio Griffa]], whose work had not been shown in New York since the 1970s.<ref name=\"to\">Carlin, T.J. [http://newyork.timeout.com/arts-culture/art/71103/casey-kaplan \"Casey Kaplan\"] ''Time Out New York,'' May 3, 2010</ref><ref>[[Roberta Smith]] (April 16, 2015), [https://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/17/arts/design/10-galleries-to-visit-in-chelsea.html 10 Galleries to Visit in Chelsea] ''[[New York Times]]''.</ref><ref>Kelly Crow (August 29, 2013), [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324009304579040852969471002 Attack of the Giant Art Galleries] ''[[Wall Street Journal]]''.</ref>\n\n==Artists==\nCasey Kaplan Gallery represents several living artists, including:\n* [[Kevin Beasley]]\n* [[Matthew Brannon]]\n* Jeff Burton, Nathan Carter\n* [[Jordan Casteel]] (since 2016)<ref>Alex Greenberger (December 15, 2016), [https://www.artnews.com/art-news/market/casey-kaplan-gallery-now-represents-jordan-casteel-7490/ Casey Kaplan Now Represents Jordan Casteel]\u00a0''[[ARTnews]]''.</ref>\n* [[Sarah Crowner]] (since 2014)<ref>Dan Duray (September 19, 2014), [https://www.artnews.com/art-news/news/sarah-crowner-to-casey-kaplan-2834/ Sarah Crowner to Casey Kaplan] ''[[ARTnews]]''.</ref>\n* N. Dash (since 2015)<ref>Andrew Russeth (January 28, 2015), [https://www.artnews.com/art-news/news/n-dash-joins-casey-kaplan-in-new-york-3510/ N. Dash Joins Casey Kaplan in New York] ''[[ARTnews]]''.</ref>\n* Jason Dodge\n* [[Judith Eisler]] (since 2017)<ref>Andrew Russeth (November 20, 2017), [https://www.artnews.com/art-news/news/judith-eisler-joins-casey-kaplan-gallery-9360/ Judith Eisler Joins Casey Kaplan Gallery] ''[[ARTnews]]''.</ref>\n* [[Haris Epaminonda]]\n* [[Geoffrey Farmer]]\n* Jonathan Gardner\n* [[Liam Gillick]]\n* [[Giorgio Griffa]]\n* [[Brian Jungen]]\n* Hannah Levy (since 2019)<ref>Andrew Russeth (February 26, 2019), [https://www.artnews.com/art-news/market/casey-kaplan-adds-hannah-levy-roster-11988/ Casey Kaplan Adds Hannah Levy to Roster] ''[[ARTnews]]''.</ref>\n* Mateo L\u00f3pez\n* [[Jonathan Monk]]\n* Marlo Pascual\n* Diego Perrone\n* [[Matthew Ronay]] (since 2017)<ref>Alex Greenberger (September 6, 2017), [https://www.artnews.com/art-news/market/matthew-ronay-is-now-represented-by-casey-kaplan-8927/ Matthew Ronay Is Now Represented by Casey Kaplan] ''[[ARTnews]]''.</ref>\n* Hugh Scott-Douglas\n* [[Simon Starling]]\n* [[David_Thorpe_(artist)|David Thorpe]]\n* [[Garth Weiser]]<ref> [http://caseykaplangallery.com/cat/artists/]</ref>\n\n==Art Fairs==\nThe gallery has exhibited at the ADAA Art Show (New York, NY)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://artdealers.org/the-art-show/exhibitors|title=Exhibitors - The Art Show - ADAA|website=artdealers.org|access-date=2020-03-01}}</ref>; [[Art Basel]] ([[Basel]], Switzerland);<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120514031304/http://www.artbasel.com/go/id/kos/ Exhibition Sectors]. MCH Swiss Exhibition (Basel) Ltd.</ref> [[Art Basel Miami Beach]] ([[Miami Beach, Florida]]);<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160317151100/https://www.artbasel.com/catalog/gallery/1083 Gallery: Casey Kaplan]. MCH Swiss Exhibition (Basel) Ltd.</ref> [[Frieze Art Fair|Frieze LA]] (Los Angeles, CA)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://frieze.com/article/galleries-announced-frieze-los-angeles-2020|title=Galleries Announced for Frieze Los Angeles 2020|website=Frieze|language=en|access-date=2020-03-01}}</ref>; [[Frieze New York]] (New York, NY)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://frieze.com/fairs/frieze-new-york/galleries?title_field_value=casey&field_gallery_fl_fair_section_value=All&field_gallery_fm_fair_section_value=All&field_gallery_fny_fair_section_value=All&field_field_gallery_fla_fair_sec_value=All&city=&starts_with=All|title=Galleries|website=frieze.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-01}}</ref>; and [[Frieze Art Fair|Frieze London]] (London, UK).<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20130529060907/http://friezelondon.com/news/frieze-london-new-design-for-2013 Frieze London 2013: Gallery List]. Frieze.</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.caseykaplangallery.com/ Official site]\n\n{{coord|40|44|49.41|N|74|0|22.83|W|type:landmark_region:US-NY|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Art galleries in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:1995 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Art galleries established in 1995]]\n[[Category:Chelsea, Manhattan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2015}}\n'''Casey Kaplan''' is a contemporary [[art gallery]] in [[New York City]], in the United States.\n\n==History==\nThe gallery was founded in 1995 in a {{convert|500|sqft|m2|abbr=on}}, one-room space located on the upper flo