mi Beach]] ([[Miami Beach, Florida]]);<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160317151100/https://www.artbasel.com/catalog/gallery/1083 Gallery: Casey Kaplan]. MCH Swiss Exhibition (Basel) Ltd.</ref> [[Frieze Art Fair|Frieze LA]] (Los Angeles, CA)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://frieze.com/article/galleries-announced-frieze-los-angeles-2020|title=Galleries Announced for Frieze Los Angeles 2020|website=Frieze|language=en|access-date=2020-03-01}}</ref>; [[Frieze New York]] (New York, NY)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://frieze.com/fairs/frieze-new-york/galleries?title_field_value=casey&field_gallery_fl_fair_section_value=All&field_gallery_fm_fair_section_value=All&field_gallery_fny_fair_section_value=All&field_field_gallery_fla_fair_sec_value=All&city=&starts_with=All|title=Galleries|website=frieze.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-01}}</ref>; and [[Frieze Art Fair|Frieze London]] (London, UK).<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20130529060907/http://friezelondon.com/news/frieze-london-new-design-for-2013 Frieze London 2013: Gallery List]. Frieze.</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.caseykaplangallery.com/ Official site]\n\n{{coord|40|44|49.41|N|74|0|22.83|W|type:landmark_region:US-NY|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Art galleries in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:1995 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Art galleries established in 1995]]\n[[Category:Chelsea, Manhattan]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toChelsea(link changed toChelsea, Manhattan) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Casey_Kaplan"}
{"title_page": "Udumalai Narayana Kavi", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2013}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{one source|date=August 2013}}\n{{cleanup reorganize|date=August 2013}}\n{{more citations needed|date=August 2013}}\n}}\n{{infobox person\n|name =Udumala Narayana Kavi\n| image=Udumalai Narayana Kavi 2008 stamp of India.jpg\n|birth_name =Udumalai Narayanan\n|birth_date =25 September 1899\n|birth_place =Poolavadi, Udumalpet taluk, Tiruppur district, Tamil Nadu\n|death_date =1981\n|occupation =poet\n}}\n'''[[Udumalpet|Udumalai]] Narayana Kavi''' (1899\u20131981) was a [[Tamil language|tamil]] [[poet]].\n\n==Early life==\nUdumalai Narayana was born on 25 September 1899 in Poolavadi, a small village in Udumalpet taluk, [[Tiruppur district]], [[Tamil Nadu]], [[India]]. His parents died at a very young age and poverty deprived him of school. With the help of his brother, he made a small living selling matchboxes to the nearby villages. Even when young he had a keen interest in play and music. He initially started off acting in plays at the local temple and then got connected with some leading play groups in Tamil Nadu. Today's Kollywood is an amalgamation of several of those play groups.\n\n==Songwriting==\nHe is best known for writing several lyrics that were used in the freedom movement in his early days and between 1950 and 1972. He wrote lyrics for several [[Tamil language|Tamil]] movies.<ref>Sundararaj Theodore Baskaran ''The eye of the serpent: an introduction to Tamil cinema'' 1996 Page 215   \" Udumalai Narayana Kavi   ... He entered films and wrote the dialogues and songs for [[Krishna Leela]] (1933). ... N.S.Krishnan invited him to work in his film Izhanda Kathal (1941). More of Krishnan's films followed. Narayana Kavi's atheistic and rationalistic ideas came to be expressed through songs. Through N.S. Krishnan, he got to know about C.N. Annadurai.\"</ref>\nSeveral of the movies that he wrote lyrics for were box office hits including ''Velaikari'', ''Nallathambi'', ''Poompuhar'', ''Manohara''. He was affectionately known as \"Kaviraayar\" in the movie industry. He was also associated with [[N. S. Krishnan]] the famous comedian in the 1940s. In Manohara, he was paid 15000 per song , which was highly paid in those days.  He written only for PUC Chinnappa , while Papanasam sivam written songs for Thiyagaraja bhagavathar.\n\n==Filmography==\n{{Expand list|date=April 2017}}\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n#''[[Kannagi (film)|Kannagi]]'' (1942)\n#''[[Tamizhariyum Perumal]]'' (1942)\n#''[[Kubera Kuchela]]'' (1943)\n#''[[Vidyapathi (1946 film)|Vidyapathi]]'' (1946)\n#''[[Vikatayogi]]'' (1946)\n#''[[Paithiyakkaran]]'' (1947)\n#''[[Rajakumari (1947 film)|Rajakumari]]'' (1947)\n#''[[Krishna Bakthi]]'' (1949)\n#''[[Nallathambi]]'' (1949)\n#''[[Pavalakkodi (1949 film)|Pavalakodi]]'' (1949)\n#''[[Velaikkaari]]'' (1949)\n#''[[Parijatham (1950 film)|Parijatham]]'' (1950)\n#''[[Vijayakumari (film)|Vijayakumari]]'' (1950)\n#''[[Manamagal]]'' (1951)\n#''[[Marmayogi]]'' (1951)\n#''[[Vanasundari]]'' (1951)\n#''[[Panam (film)|Panam]]'' (1952)\n#''[[Parasakthi (film)|Parasakthi]] (1952)\n#''[[Devadasu (1953 film)|Devadas]] (1953)\n#''[[Marumagal (1953 film)|Marumagal]]'' (1953)\n#''[[Ponni (1953 film)|Ponni]]'' (1953)\n#''[[Manohara (film)|Manohara]]'' (1954)\n#''[[Penn (film)|Penn]]'' (1954)\n#''[[Ratha Kanneer]]'' (1954)\n#''[[Sorgavasal]]'' (1954)\n#''[[Thookku Thookki]]'' (1954)\n#''[[Chella Pillai]]'' (1955)\n#''[[Doctor Savithri]]'' (1955)\n#''[[Kaveri (1955 film)|Kaveri]]'' (1955)\n#''[[Mangaiyar Thilakam]]'' (1955)\n#''[[Mudhal Thethi]]'' (1955)\n#''[[Needhipathi]]'' (1955)\n#''[[Aasai (1956 film)|Aasai]]'' (1956)\n#''[[Amara Deepam (1956 film)|Amara Deepam]]'' (1956)\n#''[[Madurai Veeran (1956 film)|Madurai Veeran]]'' (1956)\n#''[[Mathar Kula Manickam]]'' (1956)\n#''[[Rangoon Radha]]'' (1956)\n#''[[Engal Veettu Mahalakshmi]]'' (1957)\n#''[[Karpukkarasi]]'' (1957)\n#''[[Bommai Kalyanam]]'' (1958)\n#''[[Mangalya Bhagyam]]'' (1958)\n#''[[Abalai Anjugam]]'' (1959)\n#''[[Amudhavalli]]'' (1959)\n#''[[Mamiyar Mechina Marumagal]]'' (1959)\n#''[[Manjal Mahimai]]'' (1959)\n#''[[Nalla Theerpu]]'' (1959)\n#''[[Pudhumai Penn (1959 film)|Pudhumai Penn]]'' (1959)\n#''[[Thaai Magalukku Kattiya Thaali]]'' (1959)\n#''[[Thanga Padhumai]]'' (1959)\n#''[[Chavukkadi Chandrakantha]]'' (1960)\n#''[[Deivapiravi]]'' (1960)\n#''[[Pattaliyin Vetri]]'' (1960)\n#''[[Raja Desingu]]'' (1960)\n#''[[Arasilangkumari]]'' (1961)\n#''[[Chittoor Rani Padmini]]'' (1963)\n#''[[Poompuhar (film)|Poompuhar]]'' (1964)\n#''[[Chitthi]]'' (1966)\n#''[[Vivasayee]]'' (1967)\n#''[[Aathi Parasakthi]]'' (1971)\n#''[[Kurathi Magan]]'' (1972)\n#''[[Dasavatharam (film)|Dasavatharam]] (1976)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Respect==\nIn respect for his contribution to Tamil and its people, the government of [[Tamil Nadu]] has erected a memorial for him at [[Udumalaipettai]].<ref>[http://www.tn.gov.in/tamiltngov/memorial/default.htm Memorials of Eminent Personalities<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> What made Narayana Kavi very popular was his ability to use simple language that could be understood even by peasants. He died in 1981.\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.indiapost.gov.in/Stamps2008.aspx India Post 31 December 2008: A commemorative postage stamp on UDUMALAI NARAYANA KAVI]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kavi}}\n[[Category:1899 births]]\n[[Category:1981 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian poets]]\n[[Category:Indian male poets]]\n[[Category:Poets from Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:People from Tirupur district]]\n[[Category:Indian lyricists]]\n[[Category:Tamil film poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2013}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{one source|date=August 2013}}\n{{cleanup reorganize|date=August 2013}}\n{{more citations needed|date=August 2013}}\n}}\n{{infobox person\n|name =Udumala Narayana Kavi\n| image=Udumalai Narayana Kavi 2008 stamp of India.jpg\n|birth_name =Udumalai Narayanan\n|birth_date =25 September 1899\n|birth_place =Poolavadi, Udumalpet taluk, Tiruppur district, Tamil Nadu\n|death_date =1981\n|occupation =poet\n}}\n'''[[Udumalpet|Udumalai]] Narayana Kavi''' (1899\u20131981) was a [[Tamil language|tamil]] [[poet]].\n\n==Early life==\nUdumalai Narayana was born on 25 September 1899 in Poolavadi, a small village in Udumalpet taluk, [[Tiruppur district]], [[Tamil Nadu]], [[India]]. His parents died at a very young age and poverty deprived him of school. With the help of his brother, he made a small living selling matchboxes to the nearby villages. Even when young he had a keen interest in play and music. He initially started off acting in plays at the local temple and then got connected with some leading play groups in Tamil Nadu. Today's Kollywood is an amalgamation of several of those play groups.\n\n==Songwriting==\nHe is best known for writing several lyrics that were used in the freedom movement in his early days and between 1950 and 1972. He wrote lyrics for several [[Tamil language|Tamil]] movies.<ref>Sundararaj Theodore Baskaran ''The eye of the serpent: an introduction to Tamil cinema'' 1996 Page 215   \" Udumalai Narayana Kavi   ... He entered films and wrote the dialogues and songs for [[Krishna Leela]] (1933). ... N.S.Krishnan invited him to work in his film Izhanda Kathal (1941). More of Krishnan's films followed. Narayana Kavi's atheistic and rationalistic ideas came to be expressed through songs. Through N.S. Krishnan, he got to know about C.N. Annadurai.\"</ref>\nSeveral of the movies that he wrote lyrics for were box office hits including ''Velaikari'', ''Nallathambi'', ''Poompuhar'', ''Manohara''. He was affectionately known as \"Kaviraayar\" in the movie industry. He was also associated with [[N. S. Krishnan]] the famous comedian in the 1940s. In Manohara, he was paid 15000 per song , which was highly paid in those days.  He written only for PUC Chinnappa , while Papanasam sivam written songs for Thiyagaraja bhagavathar.\n\n==Filmography==\n{{Expand list|date=April 2017}}\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n#''[[Kannagi (film)|Kannagi]]'' (1942)\n#''[[Tamizhariyum Perumal]]'' (1942)\n#''[[Kubera Kuchela]]'' (1943)\n#''[[Vidyapathi (1946 film)|Vidyapathi]]'' (1946)\n#''[[Vikatayogi]]'' (1946)\n#''[[Paithiyakkaran]]'' (1947)\n#''[[Rajakumari (1947 film)|Rajakumari]]'' (1947)\n#''[[Krishna Bakthi]]'' (1949)\n#''[[Nallathambi]]'' (1949)\n#''[[Pavalakkodi (1949 film)|Pavalakodi]]'' (1949)\n#''[[Velaikkaari]]'' (1949)\n#''[[Parijatham (1950 film)|Parijatham]]'' (1950)\n#''[[Vijayakumari (film)|Vijayakumari]]'' (1950)\n#''[[Manamagal]]'' (1951)\n#''[[Marmayogi]]'' (1951)\n#''[[Vanasundari]]'' (1951)\n#''[[Panam (film)|Panam]]'' (1952)\n#''[[Parasakthi (film)|Parasakthi]] (1952)\n#''[[Devadasu (1953 film)|Devadas]] (1953)\n#''[[Marumagal (1953 film)|Marumagal]]'' (1953)\n#''[[Ponni (1953 film)|Ponni]]'' (1953)\n#''[[Manohara (film)|Manohara]]'' (1954)\n#''[[Penn (film)|Penn]]'' (1954)\n#''[[Ratha Kanneer]]'' (1954)\n#''[[Sorgavasal]]'' (1954)\n#''[[Thookku Thookki]]'' (1954)\n#''[[Chella Pillai]]'' (1955)\n#''[[Doctor Savithri]]'' (1955)\n#''[[Kaveri (1955 film)|Kaveri]]'' (1955)\n#''[[Mangaiyar Thilakam]]'' (1955)\n#''[[Mudhal Thethi]]'' (1955)\n#''[[Needhipathi]]'' (1955)\n#''[[Aasai (1956 film)|Aasai]]'' (1956)\n#''[[Amara Deepam (1956 film)|Amara Deepam]]'' (1956)\n#''[[Madurai Veeran (1956 film)|Madurai Veeran]]'' (1956)\n#''[[Mathar Kula Manickam]]'' (1956)\n#''[[Rangoon Radha]]'' (1956)\n#''[[Engal Veettu Mahalakshmi]]'' (1957)\n#''[[Karpukkarasi]]'' (1957)\n#''[[Bommai Kalyanam]]'' (1958)\n#''[[Mangalya Bhagyam]]'' (1958)\n#''[[Abalai Anjugam]]'' (1959)\n#''[[Amudhavalli]]'' (1959)\n#''[[Mamiyar Mechina Marumagal]]'' (1959)\n#''[[Manjal Mahimai]]'' (1959)\n#''[[Nalla Theerpu]]'' (1959)\n#''[[Pudhumai Penn (1959 film)|Pudhumai Penn]]'' (1959)\n#''[[Thaai Maga